 <br>
Foreword<br>
<br>
Greetings fellow wizard! You hold in your hands the collective knowledge of many great sorcerers who have traveled the many different paths of Norrath, its moon and even the alternate Planes. <br>
<br>
Our abilities or usefulness may not always be evident to our counterparts. We might not be “required” for survival in a dungeon siege, as perhaps a cleric or enchanter may be. This might make companionship hard to come by, not because of our quality of character, but because of the gross misconception of our abilities.<br>
<br>
Fret not evoker! You have huge potential to take your growth and advancement into your own hands. The powerful abilities you currently possess or are destined to obtain will aid you in greater progression than is possible in any other profession. <br>
<br>
We, as wizards have the potential for enormous power and the key to that achievement is primarily obtained via the knowledge we possess. Better knowledge enables us to attain tremendous power. <br>
<br>
Through the difficult yet profitable technique of “quad-kiting” you can empower yourself with growth at a rate staggering to most of your companions. The time you take to seek this knowledge and master its technique will pay you back tenfold.<br>
<br>
Perhaps the single most challenging aspect of “quad-kiting” to master is the understanding of where it is most lucrative to engage in. Here we present you with that knowledge . . .all in one handy printed and bound volume. The collective experience of the Sorcerers united by Graffe.  We offer you here the wisdom we have acquired in the quest to perfect the art of quad kiting.<br>
<br>
Use it well brothers. Be courteous to each other and good journeys.<br>
<br>
Respectfully Submitted,<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
 Shafli Tritium of Elder Fellowship<br>
<br>
 <br>
24-31, Lake of Ill Omen<br>
Minimum Level: 24<br>
Maximum Level: 31<br>
Zone Name: Lake of Ill Omen<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Northwest Ruins by the lake shore<br>
Mob List (HP): Goblins<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 8 (popular for low level wizards)<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 1<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 3 (must have SoW, a little difficult w/o BoF)<br>
Faction Affected: Goblins decreased, Iksar increased<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: I learned to quad here, it's extremely simple and a pre-packaged quad-kite. I had a hotkey to tell the zone, given the idiot ratio in LoIO, when I was quadding. Plus OT and FM are right nearby, and you can sometimes get into a Sarnak group<br>
<br>
I suggest binding at the mill; it's a bit of a run to the ruins, but it makes it easier when your SoW/clarity runs out, or when a pull goes bad. Keep root and gate up at all times, and watch for roamers.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Atelen<br>
<br>
 <br>
29-34, Great Divide<br>
Minimum Level: 29<br>
Maximum Level: 34<br>
Zone Name: Great Divide<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Tizmak Caves #1-#3, (Left on the wall from the waterfall)<br>
Mob List (HP): Tizmaks of all Shapes and Sizes<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 10<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 4 <br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 6 <br>
Faction Affected: Lowers Tizmak faction, which cannot be re-raised, but serves no useful purpose other than keeping them from agro-ing you if you run by them later.<br>
<br>
Fairly good place to learn to quad as there is very little chance of getting an add unless you've hosed your Coldain faction somehow by this level. You usually have to pull them down off the hill to the flatter land otherwise you get targeting issues. I use Column of Lightning and drop them in about five casts. Cave #1 has a LOT of Tizzies. You can usually pull the four at the entrance with no problem though. Cave 2 only has two spawns at the entrance so it's good, safe, steady kiting. Cave 3 has from 3-4 mobs, depending on where the runner is.<br>
<br>
NOTES:<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I've never had a problem getting one of the three caves. One of them is almost always open.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp They sometimes drop velium weapons that will sell for 3-6 plat in Shadowhaven. No coin, though.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp They run fast. Will also get a caster sometimes that can ruin a quad. <br>
<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Aruvius<br>
<br>
NOTES: Great Divide, wolves around the Luclin spires are very doable. Avoid giants. I was doing this in the mid and upper 40's before I learned about spirocs. Low loot, medium difficulty. XP isn't great, but includes useful faction.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Awlin<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <br>
29-34, Marus Seru<br>
Minimum Level: 29<br>
Maximum Level: 34<br>
Zone Name: Marus Seru<br>
Camp Area/LOC: The plains just outside the Sanctus Seru zone entrance<br>
Mob List(HP) : Greyhoppers; Zelniaks; Lightcrawlers*<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 10<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 1 <br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 4 <br>
Faction Affected: None<br>
<br>
*Stonegrabbers also, if you feel especially brave, but there are a lot of stonegrabbers and they are very social. I have not tried because it does not seem worth the effort with so many other easier things to pick on. But the looting would be better--they drop gold earrings occasionally. If you are careful you can avoid all the extras that would agro. They also drop armor dying materials. The stonegrabbers are still dark blue with the occasional light blue at level 34, so I imagine the area is viable through 35, but probably not worth it with Overthere and other areas listed that are, in my humble opinion, better.)<br>
<br>
My main interest in quad-kiting here is because I was a master tailor before I took my long break, and wanted an easy place to collect pelts to take me to a moderate level again without spending too much plat. The greyhoppers drop low quality hides frequently and regular hides almost as frequently. My tailor skill went from about 20 to 88ish here over the course my XP'ing.<br>
<br>
These critters start to turn light blue at 30 (but I'm currently 31 and have not yet found a green hopper or lightcrawler; some green zelniaks), so XP wise it may not be terribly worth it to you.<br>
<br>
The camp area is very wide open though, with hills around the edges (that you should avoid because of the usual pathing and line-of-sight issues). Very minimal danger of adds if you pay attention and rarely will you have people complaining about you.<br>
<br>
I tried north of the Neth Lair entrance a lot, but there is too much hilly terrain and too many chances for adds there for my taste. <br>
<br>
NOTES:<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp For newbie quadkiters the long agro range of zelniaks can be difficult to get used to. (EDIT: a &quot;gigantic lightcrawler&quot; that cannot be rooted and runs faster than blood of the wolf SoW occasionally spawns here, too.) For people like me, returned from a long break and starting over, it shouldn't be too difficult.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp There are so many mobs and so few people here (on my server, at least) that availability has never been an issue for me.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp No coin or &quot;interesting&quot; items in my experience. Various caster research items (runes, pages, and such), pelts, and hides.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Lanoril <br>
 <br>
29-36, Southern Karana<br>
Minimum Level: 29<br>
Maximum Level: 36<br>
Zone Name: South Karanas<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Paw Spires<br>
Mob List: Tech'Mal Gnolls<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 3 <br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 6 <br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 2 <br>
Faction Affected: Tesch'Mal Gnolls decreased, Increases with Karana Residents, and some others.<br>
<br>
As long as you can find it open, Paw is a very easy place to kite. If you can, get the center or north spire, as there are multiple pops there. If the whole of Paw is uncamped (I get lucky in off-hours sometimes) then it's an xp goldmine, not to mention you can make some fairly decent cash as well.<br>
<br>
NOTES:<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Usually pretty heavily camped.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp They can drop Fine Steel weapons plus 2-3 plat and change.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Aruvius <br>
 <br>
34-43, Eastern Wastes<br>
Minimum Level: 34<br>
Maximum Level: 43<br>
Zone Name: Eastern Wastes<br>
Camp Area/LOC: The shore north of the bridge<br>
Mob List (HP): Walruses, Uthork Hunters, Uthork Warriors <br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 5 <br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 6 <br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 2 <br>
Faction Affected: Othmir increased, Uthorks/Bulthars decreased<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: Avoid the rhinos, they run very fast, and are quite resistant to spells. Begin with the walruses, and as they become light blue, move up to Uthork Hunters and then Uthork Warriors. If you can only find two (2) dark blue mobs, you might as well mix in a couple light blue or greens to keep the spawns cycling and you'll be using the mana anyway, so it's extra kills for free. Have something to make you run fast, and use Bonds of Force (level 29) to snare and the researched Circle of Force (level 34) to nuke.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Great place to learn how to quad, plenty of room, easy to avoid adds.<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Sometimes hard to find four (4) mobs due to other quadders.<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Tusks can be traded in Cobalt Scar for gems, occasional research drops.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Hraveob<br>
<br>
NOTE: I was told by another Wizzie that the Wooly Rhino's in EW are *not* that fast and could be included in a quad. Can't confirm this, might go check this myself. <br>
<br>
Submitted by: Traxam<br>
<br>
NOTE: EW was good as early as 34 on walrus up to 44 or so. Rhinos run exactly as fast as ulthorks and you can mix the quads. They are not social in the same way, so you will need to finish them a little differently. For walrus, there's another/better location south of Kael entrance. Many walrus, plenty of space. Avoid man-o-war. Less space than north shore, but less competition and all walrus. No waiting for spawns.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Awlin<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <br>
34-42, Dawnshroud Peaks<br>
Minimum Level: 34<br>
Maximum Level: 42<br>
Zone Name: Dawnshroud Peaks<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Sanctus Sseru zone line<br>
Mob List (HP): Zelniaks (moose), shrooms, lightcrawlers<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 7<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 1<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 5<br>
Faction Affected: None<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: Good place to learn to quad. The small Zelniaks just north of the Sseru zone line are easy and non-social. You can spread out to the middle of the zone as you approach level 40.<br>
<br>
The non-social nature of the Zelniak tends to make finishing a quad annoying.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Mes2k<br>
 <br>
34-42, The Overthere<br>
Minimum Level: 34<br>
Maximum Level: 42 <br>
Zone Name: The Overthere<br>
Camp Area/LOC: West and South sides<br>
Mob List (HP): Sarnaks, Succulant, Cockatrice<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 6 (depends on pull groups)<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 3<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 6 (Rhinos/Cats/SoW'd Sarnaks)<br>
Faction Affected: Sarnaks<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: This is a great zone to learn to quad in. The mobs are plentiful and the spawn times high. The easiest things to quad are Sarnaks; start with berserkers and move up to knights.<br>
<br>
Sarnaks - Social; if there is more than one (1) they will chase you forever, if there's only one and it is snared it will freeze.<br>
<br>
Succulants - Non-social; if they are close and low and snared they will stand still. These will wander off if you leave a certain radius so keep them close when you're finishing a quad. Get them all low and the same time and they will all freeze in a group giving you an easy finish.<br>
<br>
Cockatrice - See Succulants<br>
<br>
The main dangers here are the adds. Rhinos and cats are SoW speed. If you pick one up, dart up a hill/rock and Shadow Step then gate or root it fast and zone out. There are a ton of wandering mobs as well, so keep your eyes open. You can quad along the southern hillside with few wanderers between the Frontier Mountain zone line (ledge) and the SE corner. Another great line is along the gorge running north and south since it is almost devoid of wanderers.<br>
<br>
I have found that grabbing a mob then running ahead, invising up and then looking for more worked great. It kept down the adds until I chose to break invis and the tagged mobs continued to follow. Only Sarnaks will add on their friends, so it greatly minimizes your risk while tagging mobs. <br>
<br>
Submitted by: Chifiir <br>
<br>
<br>
NOTE: There's another danger here; sometimes the Sarnaks are SoWed here. To make sure one isn't *don't* pull it while it's standing still but look at it walk. <br>
<br>
Submitted by: Traxam<br>
<br>
 <br>
34-43, Iceclad (near Dragon Bridge)<br>
Minimum Level: 34<br>
Maximum Level: 43<br>
Zone Name: Iceclad<br>
Camp Area/LOC: By the Eastern Wastes Dragon Bridge<br>
Mob List (HP): Dire Wolves, Snow Dervishes<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 9 (I’ve only &quot;competed&quot; for quads once)<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 1<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 2 (easy quadding, only real problem is pulling if you've got bad giant faction)<br>
Faction Affected: None<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: I learned to quad here, and made it my home from 35 to 42. The southwestern side of the EW Bridge island is fairly flat and free of trees, which lets you learn how to wrap pretty well. Just don't get spoiled on the vast, wide-open spaces! There are some nice ice floes way down south you can sit and med on (and practice your fishing, too.) Just don't annoy any turtles you see spinning around down there.<br>
<br>
You may have difficulty with your first few pulls if you've already tarnished your giant faction; roaming Frost Giant Scouts will force you to weave and bob as you try to snag that fourth Dire Wolf. JBoots or some form of SoW a must. Just remember that safety is just over that bridge!<br>
<br>
Beware of the Dire Wolf Stalker, a higher-level wolf than the others that can throw off your quad, and a pack of Kromrif tracking wolves (who appear by the bridge when someone's doing the eighth shawl quest), which will be very, very red to you.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Frotz Nitfol<br>
<br>
 <br>
36-42, Iceclad (outside ToFS)<br>
Minimum Level: 36<br>
Maximum Level: 42<br>
Zone Name: Iceclad<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Outside Tower of Frozen Shade<br>
Mob List (HP): Shadows<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 10 (very FAST respawn)<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 3  (a few frost daggers, pp, and so on)<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 3<br>
Faction Affected: None<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: Bind at the doggy camp, to TP easily to get SoWs and so on.<br>
<br>
Don't go Anon...People stuck in this zone usually are ready to pay a good price to get TP’ed/TL’ed out. <br>
<br>
Pull with the taunt stick (tflux), get them rounded up on the clear area right between ToFS, the doggy camp and the shore watch out for a named shadow, Blizzard or something, the thingy DDs from afar, very annoying. Not a big DD, but since quadding takes time, you get dead fast. Never seen levels pass this fast, the XP there is insane.<br>
<br>
May I add I never got any competition at this spot? Paradise it is, my fellow wizards, believe me.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Sastiss<br>
<br>
NOTE: Iceclad, panthers. I taught myself to kite on these guys in the low 30's before moving on to dervishes. Camp site is the pirate island. Low loot, low-medium difficulty. Pull them to the island's edge and kite along it to avoid wanderers. You can quad them at 34, or dervishes, but you get better loot &amp; exp from EW walrus at that level.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Awlin<br>
<br>
<br>
 <br>
38-49, Oasis &amp; OOT (Spectre Islands)<br>
Minimum Level: 38<br>
Maximum Level: 49<br>
Zone Name: Oasis<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Oasis (Spectre Island) &amp; OOT<br>
Mob List (HP): ~1800<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 7 (rarely camped)<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 5 (occasional gems, 3pp)<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 2 (very easy due to slow movement)<br>
Faction Affected: None<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: There are 4 spectres on the island on each corner. Just grab levitate and tflux them and run around in circles. Once they are snared you can quad them on the island, but if you are nervous just run them to the south shore and quad there. I have never had a spectre agro someone else during a pull and it impresses the hell out of some people.<br>
<br>
There are four (4) more spectres in the tower, one (1) on the bottom and three (3) up top. You can target and pull the spectres up top through the walls, since you can see them sticking out through the walls. Just tflux them and keep running. Mostly light blue to 49, but before that its all dark blue.<br>
<br>
Two (2) quads per 15 minute respawn, can sell/buy bandages at gypsies or the inn depending if you are evil and good. Oasis is a fun zone too. If you get bored you can slay a Sand Giant for some pp. Nice camp!<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Adon Borealis<br>
<br>
NOTE: Spectres, from my xperience, are not quaddable after the PoP patches. The range on their life-tap is now very large, making it impossible to keep them grouped as they keep life-tapping you. While the life tap is only 30 some odd points, having 4 specs constantly life-tapping you from afar makes you dead quick.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Raelar Arcanus<br>
<br>
NOTE: Same mobs and strategies can be applied to the specters in Ocean of Tears. What makes these an attractive camp is that they are the highest level monsters in the area which leads to very few adds. The OOT is exactly four (4) spectres, so there might be down-time in between runs (about a 15-20 minute respawn)<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Anda Shinycoat<br>
