52-60, Skyfire Mountains<br>
Minimum Level: 52 (depending on gear I think)<br>
Maximum Level: 60<br>
Zone Name: Skyfire Mountains<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Any zone wall (might want to stick to OT and BW zone areas to run to if things go awry)<br>
Mob List (HP): Bottomless Gnawers, Feasterers, Gnashsers, and Devourers, Wyverns, Wurms, Skyash Drakes. <br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 8 (constant selection of mobs available)<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 8 <br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 8 <br>
Faction Affected: None<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: Despite the changes to the Chromadracs dispell, SF is still a spot we can quad in. It takes some time and skill but it is doable. With the Changes to Chromadracs I seriously advise getting Run3 before making SF your home for quadding. You get your SoW dispelled and you are in trouble here and will be dead pretty quick. Also try to keep a skin up at all times, mobs hit pretty hard here. <br>
<br>
The edges of the zone tend to have a few spots that are not filled with wanderers and tend to be flat without a lot of big boulders in the way. Find these spots and do your quadding runs here. I've done multiple quads with various mobs thrown together and am able to get them all snared with no problem.<br>
<br>
If you get a resist or miss a snare on a mob, simply run ahead a little, root it, and then break root by tapping mob with Shock of Ice. Proceed to round up the quad from there, you may or may not have to resnare before all of the mobs drop (I do at 50% health just to be safe)<br>
<br>
A note on Chromadracs: While Verant gave them the ability to dispell at casting range this has merely taken them out of the lineup as quadding targets. The agro on Chromas seems to be a very small area. I run over the top of a hill and stop right in front of them all of the time, just be sure to turn tail and run like the wind in the opposite direction.<br>
Make sure you put your important buffs like SoW, C3, Ageo, etc behind as many dummy buffs as possible. This reduces the chance of accidentally losing them if you aggro a Chroma. If anything, quadding in SF while teach you how to really drive a quad with finesse. What I mean by this is that I prefer to have a full quad when I am kiting so I end up running around a bit tagging mobs here and there to make a full quad. Dodging Chromas and steering my unsnared quad around Chromas has taken quadding to a whole new level for me. Quadding in CS made me complacent, quadding in SF honed my skills to a sharp edge.<br>
<br>
Oh yeah, one final note... if you happen to see Talendor and are in the middle of a quad, take you quad away from him and with a quickness. His aggro range is a tad large and you can aggro him by pulling near him.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Spell drops and an average of 8pp or so from each mob, occasional gem. Do not go /role or /anon, lots of individuals will pay nicely for TLs here.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Driz <br>
 <br>
54-58, Timorous Deep (Raptors, Part I)<br>
Minimum Level: 54<br>
Maximum Level: 58+<br>
Zone Name: Timorous Deep (PART I)<br>
Camp Name/Loc: Raptor Islands<br>
Mob List(HP): Raptors (blue til 57 (rare blue after that)) Vicious raptors (blue til 60), Dinus (level 48 I think, blue 60+)<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 2 <br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 1 (abysmal, only research components)<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 3 <br>
Faction Affected: none<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: Just south of the chessboard isle in Timorous Deep is the Raptor Isles. There are two; widely known as large and small (due to their size naturally). They are very close to each other. The easiest way into TD is to go to Firiona Vie (or Overthere) and talk to the Translocator. He will pop you into the Timorous Deep zone and you can levitate, SoW and hike it to the isles. Assuming they are not camped you have your choice of the two isles.<br>
<br>
Small- Easier to &quot;break&quot; as the sets of mobs are farther apart from eachother. There are a total of seven mobs for this island. Four on the &quot;beach&quot; side make set#1. Two on the north side of the island + 1 spare from large island make set#2. This is acceptable and xpected to pull this straggler across the water to the small isle. He is on the northern part of the large isle and is all by himself. Simply pull one set of mobs, wrap and kite. Then you have a good 12 mins. to use that side of the island to med. All raptors are on a 12 min. timer. Get in the habit of timing them and be ready for the next spawn. If you spend the time breaking the spawn up you don't wan to get caught off-guard by another set spawning while you're kiting the other half of the island. Downside of this isle is you need levitate at all times to grab the straggler and you only get seven (7) spawns (as opposed to &quot;large&quot; where you get eight (<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  for the same mana output).<br>
<br>
Large- Harder to break as the mobs aren't as separate. You need to get four and exactly four in your first pull to break the spawn. I don't have any good advice here except to be careful and scope out your pull before you do it. Levitate and use the water to your advantage. Try to kite in a tight area on one side of the island. Then you've got your 5-6 mins. to do the other side. Once the spawn is broken up you will be quadding every few minutes and should see some excellent XP!<br>
<br>
NOTE: Careful when pulling Dinus, he's got a lot more HP than the others and you might need to sit-med-nuke a few times to finish him off. This has caused problems a few times as it screws up the timing of the spawns if you take too long to kill him. If you see Dinus up you are best to wait till you are full mana before pulling the whole quad so you can finish him quickly after the first three go down. This will keep the spawning/killing times consistent.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Breaking the large isle is tough, but then it's simple after that.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Shafli<br>
 <br>
