56-60, Maiden’s Eye<br>
Minimum Level: 56 (depending on mana)<br>
Maximum Level: 60<br>
Zone Name: Maiden’s Eye<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Toiler hill<br>
Mob List (HP): Toilers (roughly 5-6K HP)<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 3<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 7 <br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 7 (takes considerable learning)<br>
Faction Affected: None<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: One tip, invis and watch the pathing to see how things work. <br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Above average loot. Some rare drops worth 500pp if you can sell them.<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Heihache <br>
<br>
 <br>
 <br>
56-58, Wakening Lands<br>
Minimum Level: 56<br>
Maximum Level: 58<br>
Zone Name: Wakening Lands<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Northern part of the map, middle of east/west boundaries<br>
Mob List (HP): Suits of Sentient Armor (8000)<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 10<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 7 (300-400 plat/hr)<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 7<br>
Faction Affected: None<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings:<br>
<br>
The XP is not that great because they have 8000+ HP's. It takes a ton of mana to finish them off, and that means lots of med time. But there are two nifty things about quadding here: Camp is always available, and loot is great. C3 and lots of +int/+mana gear is a must. Only Pillar of Lightning works reliably. Special care must be taken not to path them through a tree, as that will scatter the pack. The terrain has a rough learning curve. <br>
<br>
Submitted by: Mes2k <br>
<br>
 <br>
58-61, Western Wastes<br>
Minimum level: 58<br>
Maximum level: 61<br>
Zone Name: Western Wastes<br>
Camp Area/Loc: Entire Zone<br>
Mob List(HP): Brontotheriums (Blue to 61, Mint to 62), Glaciar Mastodons (Blue to 61, Mint to 62)<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 9<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 4 <br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 7 <br>
Faction Affected: No faction hits<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: Have Run 3. These are pretty much your last hurrah at quadding in pre-pop zones. The mobs are not social, so if you are resist or crit too much of a difference in HP some will turn while the others still chase you. You can generally just make a loop until the unturned mob or mobs join back in (they have insane regen) and then nuke them all turned at once.<br>
<br>
Velium hounds are harder to spot, but if you see several of them up there is no reason they would not be quaddable similarly.<br>
<br>
If you get a velium hound add and you are not sowed, it WILL be faster than you. Run far enough that your quad does not beat on you (4 of these mobs hitting you is unpleasant briefly), then root and snare the dog. Abandon quad if necessary, but unless you are marginal on mana, it should not really be necessary. If you are sowed you can outrun the dog, but they are fast enough that you will have to generate a lot of distance from your quad to do so. Better generally to take the hits and root/snare them, kill them, and resume your quad.<br>
<br>
NOTES:<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Mastodon Furs can be worthwhile for tailoring or selling, as can Velium Hound Furs.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Rare resists, but the mobs are not social; Primarly risk is Velium Hound adds.<br>
<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Charr <br>
 <br>
60-61, Dragon Necropolis<br>
Minimum Level: 60<br>
Maximum Level: 61<br>
Zone Name: Dragon Necropolis<br>
Camp Area/LOC: Zone In<br>
Mob List(HP) : Phase Spiders (Dark Blue to 61, Light Blue to 62)<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 8<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 4 <br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 10 <br>
Faction Affected: None<br>
<br>
Pull with Atol's. You need the time on the snare and the resist bonus and you don't want them after you at full speed.<br>
<br>
Pop traps invised, swarming beatles see invis though so avoid that trap (second ramp corner)<br>
<br>
When a spider hits you that you weren't expecting, cast Atol's on it while it is hitting you. Their melee range is such that they will start hitting you while you are still out of the range of Atol's. I've only hit myself with snare once doing this and I was dealing with multiple spiders at the time (/hug exodus).<br>
<br>
The spiders proc a phase shift (Yonder) on you. This can be disorienting. If you get confused, bail and try again. If you get ported mid-cast duck immediately and recast. Getting phase shifted is counted as a (long) movement so your cast is already blown. You can also get ported onto the bones, which hold Dragon Construct traps. Dragon Constructs stay up for days and like any dragonish thing, require melee range to cast on making them essentially un-killable by you solo.<br>
<br>
The spiders are fairly resistant so you may have to snare several times. This can be problematic with a full quad when you keep seeing one or two resist messages. <br>
<br>
Even snared these things are fast. Run the lot of them back to the zone in and in a big loop around it as you burn.<br>
<br>
Pathing when you pull is FUBAR (particularly past the first ramp) so watch and make sure they are following, you may have to back track a bit. <br>
<br>
NOTES:<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Sometimes drop Phase Spider Blood (nice for non casters) and about every 30th one or so drops a PSC.<br>
<br>
·&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I do not generally quad these intentionally, I go for two or three, and if I get an add, snare it and quad then. They run fast, hit hard, proc yonder on you, spring from traps, warp on you, warp unexpectedly in front of you while pulling others, etc. Learn where the traps are so you can pop and pull them.<br>
<br>
<br>
Submitted by: Charr <br>
 <br>
60-63, Plane of Nightmare<br>
Minimum Level: 60<br>
Maximum Level: 63<br>
Zone Name: Plane of Nightmare<br>
Camp Area/LOC: East of ZI<br>
Mob List (HP): Ravenous Nightstalkers (12-15khp)<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 3<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 10<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 7<br>
Faction Affected: none<br>
<br>
Other Notes/Tips/Warnings: These have a lot of HP, KEI, flappy, PotC, and a pretty good size mana pool is nice unless you like to med kite. Run3 is fast enough to stay ahead of them unsnared, just give yourself lots of room to snare. There are about a dozen spawns and they have a fairly large agro assist range. Take some time to figure out how to break the camp or you will find yourself with six (6) to eight (<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  mobs per pull. They can drop diamonds, blue diamonds, and raw diamonds. They start to turn light blue at 63.<br>
<br>
